The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Bikes pull down auto sales
                                                                                                            Bikes pull down auto sales
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                                            
	New Delhi, Feb. 8: Domestic automobile sales dropped 7.67 per cent in January to 8,29,569 units from 8,98,444 units in the same month last year.        
	According to data released by the Society of Indian Automobile Manufacturers (SIAM), domestic passenger car sales rose 8.99 per cent in January, while two-wheelers continued their downhill ride with a 10.96 per cent decline compared with sales in January, 2007.        
	Passenger car sales rose to 1,13,899 units from 1,04,501 units in the same month last year. Hyundai Motors led the car segment, with the new hatchback, the i10, boosting the companys overall sales, which rose 39.22 per cent to 24,296 units from 17,452 units in January 2007. Maruti Suzuki had a flat month, registering sales of 54,366 units against 54,372 units in the same month last year.        
	General Motors sales increased two-fold with its hatchback Spark continuing a good run. The companys overall sales stood at 4,030 units against 1,665 units last year.        
	Analysts said the industry as a whole continued to decelerate with high interest rates a major issue. Wherever financing and the assessment of credit worthiness of an individual is involved, the segments are badly hit as financial institutions have imposed strict criteria, said Dilip Chenoy, director-general, SIAM.        
	Total two-wheeler sales in January dipped 10.96 per cent to 6,05,455 units from 6,80,014 units in January 2007. Motorcycle sales were down 14.07 per cent to 4,81,267 units from 5,60,056 units a year ago.         
	Hero Honda reported a decline in sales of 2.2 per cent at 2,80,663 units against 2,86,963 units. Bajaj Autos sales also fell 21.78 per cent to 1,34,704 units from 1,72,217 units in January 2007. TVS Motors sales slid 56.55 per cent to 27,697 units from 63,751 units last year.        
	Scooter sales rose 3.47 per cent to 87,537 units from 84,598 units last year.                                                                                                                                        
